indicators.justification:
Canada's Fourth National Action Plan on Open Government (1) included a commitment on financial transparency and accountability, that consisted of:
- Making government budget and spending information easier to find and understand by providing more detail on budget spending plans and budget allocations by departments; 
- Improving the GC InfoBase platform to allow Canadians to easily follow funding and results for all Government of Canada programs (2); 
- Updating the Government of Canada Guidelines on the Reporting of Grants and Contributions Awards to ensure proactive disclosure of grants and contributions data continues to meet Canada's legal and policy requirements;
-Ensuring Canadians and parliamentarians have access to information on the gender and diversity impacts of budget measures by publishing GBA+ for all newly announced budget expenditures and tax measures in future budgets.

Consultations for the Fifth NAP on Open Government related to enhancing fiscal, financial, and corporate transparency reveal that the subject has been a recurring area of interest for Canadians, government stakeholders, industry and civil society.

(1) Canada's 2018-2020 National Action Plan on Open Government, 2018. https://open.canada.ca/en/content/canadas-2018-2020-national-action-plan-open-government

(2) Infobase, Government of Canada. https://www.tbs-sct.gc.ca/ems-sgd/edb-bdd/index-eng.html#about
